external_knowledge:
- "Most recent experiments" refers to experiments with the latest `tick` value at each location;
- "Positive abundance" means the species was present in the sample;
- "Positive coverage" indicates the species was observed in a significant portion of the sample;
- "Notes" provide additional context about the quality of the encounter.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(encounter_id) 
FROM species_encounters 
WHERE abundance > 10;

external_knowledge:
- 'Rich biodiversity' refers to high species richness;
- 'Data reliability' is indicated by the average data quality score;
- 'Well-studied location' refers to a location with a high number of experiments;
- 'Numerous species encounters' means a high count of species encounters in the experiment.

- "Fosters an average species abundance" refers to the average number of species encountered in the experiments being greater than 10;
- "Blossoms beyond the threshold" is a metaphorical way of saying the average abundance is greater than 10;
- "Locales and communities" refer to the location names and community numbers associated with the experiments.

- "Peak average abundance" refers to the highest average number of species observed in any single experiment;
- "Comprehensive data quality" indicates that the experiment has high-quality data, as measured by the average quality score;
- "Unique species interactions" refer to the distinct pairs of species that interact within an experiment.

- "explorer of the vast scientific landscape" refers to the user who has accessed the most experiments;
- "tread the most paths of discovery" refers to the user who has the highest count of unique experiments accessed;
- "average biodiversity they encountered along their journey" refers to the average species richness across all experiments.

- 'Blossomed with multiple experiments' refers to communities that have more than one experiment conducted;
- 'At least one publication' means the community has at least one associated publication;
- 'At least one analysis' means the community has at least one associated analysis.

- 'Voyages' refers to experiments;
- 'Pacific waters' refers to the Pacific region;
- 'Encountered more than a handful of species' means having more than 5 species encounters;
- 'Turn of the last decade' refers to the year 2010.

- 'Seagrass Meadow 1' refers to a specific location where experiments are conducted;
- 'Blossomed beyond the first rank' means the experiments are not the top-ranked experiments in terms of the number of analyses and designs;
- 'A sprig of seagrass species present' means at least one seagrass species was encountered in the experiment.

- 'Target Species' refers to a specific species of interest in ecological studies;
- 'Community' refers to a group of living organisms in a particular area;
- 'Species richness' is a measure of the number of different species in a community;
- 'Average cover' refers to the average area covered by a species in a community.

- An experiment can have multiple publications and access events;
- The `experiment_id` uniquely identifies each experiment;
- The `year` column indicates the year the experiment was conducted.

- 'Blooming with more than one publication in 2023' refers to experiments that have more than one publication in the year 2023;
- 'Gathered samples from the fertile ground of the same year' refers to experiments that have at least one sample collected in 2023;
- 'Names of the metrics they measure' refers to the metric names associated with these experiments.

- "Experiments with more than 2 replicates" refers to experiments that have been conducted more than twice to ensure reliability and consistency of results;
- "Species that have blossomed" refers to the species that have been encountered and measured in abundance during the experiments;
- "Unique code" refers to the `experiment_id` which uniquely identifies each experiment.

- "First location" refers to location_id = 1;
- "Thrived and maintained a significant presence" means an average coverage greater than 0.5;
- "Experiments conducted after 2020" refers to the year > 2020.
